Bay Area Surf Guide Your Ultimate Local Surf Adventure Guide
//Intro copy The Bay Area has several great spots for beginners to learn how to surf and for professional surfers to get eXxXtreme at. Pre and post surf grub and drinks. Here are a few of our favorites within a stone\'s throw from the surf. Stay by the beach. Here\'s a list of hotels within walking distance of the waves. There are a ton of events happening by the beach all year long. Here are some of our favorites.
//Surf spots Fort Cronkite-Rodeo Beach, Marin Mainly a shortboard spot. Sometimes good, mostly a closeout. It has it\'s days, but those are few and far between. Great spot to take a hike if the surf isn\'t good. 849VRFJ7+75 Fort Point, San Francisco Novelty spot directly under the Golden Gate Bridge. Best on a low tide with decent sized swell. Take off points shift sometimes moving directly under or even past the bridge with another bowl forming behind a rock that will show on lower tides. Don\’t surf here unless you know what your doing and can handle dirty scowls and people telling you to go home. 849VRG6F+65 Secret Spot, San Francisco It\'s everyone\'s favorite secret somewhere between Fort Point and Ocean Beach. Don\'t surf here unless you\'re ready to go shoulder-to-shoulder with everyone who hates that you\'re there. 849VQFQV+6M Ocean Beach, San Francisco 3 miles of beach breaks on the western edge of San Francisco. Not ideal for beginners. Can get world class a few times a year with a large west-northwest swell and light offshore winds from the east. Blown out or small most of spring and summer. Fall and winter is when this spot shines. 849VQF9P+JR Sharp Park Pier, Pacifica I\'ve seen some sick barrels here. I\'ve also seen some fins. 849VJGM3+8G Rockaway Beach, Pacifica Usually looks better than it actually is. Sometimes fun and usually less crowded than other spots just north or south. 849VJG52+6P Lindamar, Pacifica Beginners galore. South end of this cove is a great spot to learn how to surf with one hundred of your new friends. Middle and north end can have punchier shortboard waves. This is the spot to go during winter storms as pre-frontal south winds blow offshore here. 849VHFXX+H5 Gray Whale Cove, San Mateo County Usually pretty mellow, but the parking lot can get full on the weekend. Not great, but not bad. Fun to change it up type of spot. 849VHF7P+RC Montara Beach, Montara More beach break. Crowds aren\'t too bad. Sometimes hollow. South end and middle tend to be where surfers. 849VGFWP+W5 Mavericks, Half Moon Bay World famous big wave spot. This spot has taken several lives. This is only for experts and pros. 849VFFVX+4X
